a black metal band from holyoke
massachusetts that recently emailed me
saying yo dude check out our demo i did
and it was pretty good you got to listen
to it link in the d box this is the new
club 8 lp the people's record and these
guys are a swedish boy girl duo and
their musical taste is really all over
the map which is something that i can
really relate to adding up all their lps
eps and singles these two have quite a
few releases and they've been active
since 1995
and despite all that this is really the
first time i'm hearing about them their
earlier stuff dabbled in drum machine
pop some very light indie rock quaint
bossa nova it sounds as if these two
have given a lot of ear time to bands
like camera obscura bell and sebastian
and even novell vog but this record is
quite the surprise because it maintains
the light airy sounds of club 8's
earlier work and the strong female
vocals but
takes this very unexpected trip into
afro-pop the kind of stuff you guys may
have heard if you're a huge fan of phila
cootie or if you're aware of any of the
compilation works put out by the
fantastic fantastic record label sound
way records so this thing has a myriad
of percussion lots of very warm bass
sunny guitars very infectious vocal
chants and some very stereotypically
cheesy organ
too
and of course let's not forget the horns
club 8 really does put their own spin on
this style of music and makes it highly
accessible i would say to a western and
european audience club 8 really has done
their homework when it comes to this
style of music and have maintained a lot
of authenticity throughout this album
but if you're an afro-pop purist which i
am partially i can see as to why this lp
would turn
you off because in some ways it is a
little sanitized it is a little
simplified you know it's not exactly
like how a hawk and a hacksaw
authentically recreates music from the
eastern bloc but if you like your music
with a bit of worldly spice in the same
vein that vampire weekend sort of puts a
worldly spice into their music i can see
this thing being a perfect summer record
for you my biggest gripe about this
album is that i really can't commit to
it just because so many of the songs
either sound the same to me or simply
kind of just breeze by just strike me as
unmemorable i've sat through this album
time and time
again and yet after i sort of distance
myself from it i can't really remember
all that much about it but while it's on
it strikes me as very sweet and
enjoyable and the vocals are a little
too sedate for me from time to time and
though this is nice when i listen to it
it kind of makes me want to listen to
some real afro beat in afro pop music
but if you're looking for something that
is good mood inducing some indie pop
with an african twist some great
percussion even greater grooves some
swoon worthy vocals and at least several
standout tracks i highly recommend this
record i'm kind of feeling a decent or
light five on it i'm really on the fence
with it though there are like i said a
couple songs that really kind of strike
me as huh this is good
but let me know what you think of this
